07903nam a22011175i 9783110221749DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20102010gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)775644302  a97831102217497 a10.1515/97831102217492doi  a(DE-B1597)37275  a(OCoLC)698166948  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBS2765.52.I58 2008 7aREL0061002bisacsh04a227.8606  aBC 73572rvk0(DE-625)rvk/9645:00aPhilemon in Perspective :bInterpreting a Pauline Letter /ced. by D. Francois Tolmie. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (394 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die neutestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0171-6441 ;v16900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAbbreviations -- tTendencies in the Research on the Letter to Philemon since 1980 -- tPaul's Persuasive Prose: An Epistolary Analysis of the Letter to Philemon -- tAffects and Emotions in the Rhetoric of Pauls's Letter to Philemon: A Rhetorical-Psychological Interpretation -- t"You Will Do Even More Than I Say": On the Rhetorical Function of Stylistic Form in the Letter to Philemon -- tHow to Deal with Onesimus? Pauls's Solution within the Frame of Ancient Legal and Documentary Sources -- tThe Letter ti Philemon in the Context of Slavery in Early Christianity -- tThe Letter to Philemon as Ethical Counterpart of Pauls's Doctrine of Justification -- tLove in the Letter to Philemon -- tContextual Interpretation of the Letter to Philemon in the United States -- tPaul, Power and Philemon. "Knowing Your Place": A Postcolonial Reading -- tHierarchy and Obedience: The Legacy of the Letter to Philemon -- tThe Reception of the Letter to Philemon in the Early Church: Origen; Jerome, Chrysostom and Augustine -- tSt. Jerome's Dissertation on the Letter to Philemon -- tHonour Discourse in John Chrysostom's Exegesis of the Letter to Philemon -- tTheodore of Mopsuestia on Paul's Letter to Philemon -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is dedicated entirely to the interpretation of Paul’s Letter to Philemon. The letter is approached from a wide variety of perspectives, thus yielding several new insights into its interpretation. In a first essay the tendencies in the research on the letter since 1980 are outlined. This is followed by essays devoted to the epistolary analysis and to a rhetorical-psychological interpretation of the letter; as well as an essay devoted to the rhetorical function of stylistic form in the letter. After this there are two essays devoted to situating the letter in its ancient context: one views the letter against the background of ancient legal and documentary sources and another one against the background of slavery in early Christianity. The next two essays focus on theological aspects, namely on the letter as ethical counterpart of Paul’s doctrine of justification and on the role that love plays in the letter. Three essays focus on ideological issues: the contextual interpretation of the letter in the US, a post-colonial reading of the letter and the letter’s legacy of hierarchy and obedience. The volume concludes with four essays on the way in which the letter was interpreted by the some of the Church Fathers: Origen, Jerome, Chrystostom, Augustine and Theodore of Mopsuestia.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aEpistolographie. 4aExegese. 4aKirchenväter. 4aNeues Testament. 4aPaulinische Literatur. 4aPhilemonbrief. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aChurch Fathers.  aLetter to Philemon.  aNew Testament.  aPauline Literature.1 aArtz-Grabner, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://